snippet.textDisplay:
⚠️ALERT⚠️: The statistics in this video are deeply flawed. The metrics, such as the percentage of players to reach a specific achievement, only apply to PC players. Furthermore, the creator continues to misuse quantitative information at 0:16 by applying the 22.5% steam metric to the total (all consoles, including PC). This simply doesn't work, as the creator's data states that every copy of Elden Ring ever sold has been through Steam; this couldn't be farther from the truth. Finally, you incorrectly state that FromSoftware made $330M from players that didn't get the first achievement, which is another example of the creator applying Steam metrics to every console. Being realistic and assuming (based on the rough average of Steam ownership estimations from Gamalytic, VG Insights, and PlayTracker) that Elden Ring sold ~14.5M copies through Steam, then FromSoftware only made $195.75M. 
TL;DR 
1) Creator misuses statistics. 
2) Creator applies misused statistics to FromSoftware's profit.

This simply doesn't work, as the creator's data states that every copy of Elden Ring ever sold has been through Steam; this couldn't be farther from the truth. Finally, you incorrectly state that FromSoftware made $330M from players that didn't get the first achievement, which is another example of the creator applying Steam metrics to every console. Being realistic and assuming (based on the rough average of Steam ownership estimations from Gamalytic, VG Insights, and PlayTracker) that Elden Ring sold ~14.5M copies through Steam, then FromSoftware only made $195.75M.

snippet.textDisplay: There is a glitch on Seamless co-op where this achievement won't unlock even if you were in Roundtable Hold. The problem is that the achievement only unlocks after you speak with Melina. So if you are playing with someone and they speak with Melina after resting at the grace, you won't be able to speak with her as she doesn't spawn anymore, and even if you warp to the RH, you still won't get the achievement till you make a new save or go to NG+ and speak with her yourself.
snippet.textOriginal: There is a glitch on Seamless co-op where this achievement won't unlock even if you were in Roundtable Hold. The problem is that the achievement only unlocks after you speak with Melina. So if you are playing with someone and they speak with Melina after resting at the grace, you won't be able to speak with her as she doesn't spawn anymore, and even if you warp to the RH, you still won't get the achievement till you make a new save or go to NG+ and speak with her yourself.

snippet.textDisplay:
I was just going over the Steam player stats the other day and was surprised by the numbers. I beat the game maybe a month after launch doing the "Age of Stars" and "Elden Lord" endings. The Steam stats for both endings for other players having done the same was really low, both less than 30 percent of the total player base. Even with issues like achievements not being recorded and factoring in a margin of error, the numbers are just way too low. I just now got time to knock out Shadow of the Erdtree, and honestly it didn't take that long.

When I originally started the game back in 2022, I did a lot of exploring on the northern part of the map as soon as it was possible. I know that is probably not ideal for many people, but for me it was a great way to get OP faster for early bosses, and made the over all play through much easier after that initial 10 hours or so of grinding up north for loot, runes etc.

snippet.textDisplay: The biggest problem with From Software games is that they are advertised as hard. In reality, Dark Souls isn't even close to real hard games, but when people first join it they get confused, go in the wrong direction, and figure that the game must be too hard for them because that's what they've heard from others. It happened to me as well. I only started playing Dark Souls after following a guide for a bit and realizing that I was heading in the wrong direction all along, and only than DS1 became the best game I've ever played.

snippet.textDisplay:
depending on how you play at the start it can take a very long time to reach round table hold.
when i first played the game i thought i was being clever and adventurous and when i exited the starting area i didn't even notice varre, turned left and made my way down to the coast. i went through boks cave without a light source and inched deeper and deeper into it by memorizing the layout and enemies. i managed to beat the boss with no weapons or level upgrades without ever losing the souls. i found my first spirit spring without having torrent. i went over to the dragon communion shrine and all the while i was wondering what i was doing wrong because this can't be how the game is meant to be experienced. since i hadn't touched any other bonf....site of grace i had to walk all the way back to the starting place and then moved on past the tree sentinel to find the church and kale where finally melina made herself known to me and i could finally spend the souls.... err runes i was frantically holding onto for hours at that point. then i went to margit pretty damn fast without much leveling or exploring and my subbornness would have me trying him for at least 1h before deciding i have to go leveling. so all in all i was at least 5h in before getting to round table hold.
so yeah it could be that these people actually spent a lot of time with the game until they decided it was not for them... poor souls

Thats me. Well I did eventually get to the round table and got the whatever achievement it gave me. Still tho I had to use literal  youtube guide to get there, wasted around 5 - 7 hours. I droped the game and its still collecting dust.
I dont feel guilty in any way, I have enough stress to relieve when I come back from my retail job, this is not a type of relaxation I was hoping for. Wandering for countless hours without any meaning and hoping to find something - no thank you. Plenty of other games to play where I get "results" just by playing a couple of hours.

I may come back to this game when I have more free time (because it needs a ton of), but many new upcoming games on the horizon, so its a big maybe.

snippet.textDisplay: As a guy who’s helped five people beat Elden Ring from start to finish, I don’t think that the being of the game was executed properly. I take my guys out to East Limgrave to get gear and ashes of war. If you only follow the bonfires and experience Margit the Fell Omen with your base gear, you’ll have a bad time. If you beat all of the weaker bosses in Limgrave to understand how boss fights work and get your Crystal Tears, you’ll be MUCH better off. The starting position should’ve been on the eastern side of Limgrave in order to promote exploration and leveling up as the player makes his/her way west.
snippet.textOriginal: As a guy who’s helped five people beat Elden Ring from start to finish, I don’t think that the being of the game was executed properly. snippet.textDisplay: If 20+% of the players are giving up that quickly it's a good sign your game should have a difficulty mode option for new players. That's 20+% of the buyers who won't be buying the next game. I can understand wanting the game to be very difficult but that's revenue that will be lost in the future that could have gone to more game development. In my opinion the game should have 3 difficulty options,  one for new players, one for gamers and one for the sweats. Don't get me wrong I am a sweaty gamer and love when games offer very hard content, but I would love to show my Dad these types of games but I know he wouldn't be able to do it even though he would think the game is very cool. We shouldn't be gate keepers, we should want our favorite games to be accessible to everyone of all skill levels.
snippet.textOriginal: If 20+% of the players are giving up that quickly it's a good sign your game should have a difficulty mode option for new players. snippet.textDisplay:
Fun fact: I managed to get the achievement for beating Leonine, at the backside of Castle Morne, before I got the achievement for reaching the Roundtable Hold.

I distinctly remember playing for several hours, at that point, and thinking to myself, “Shouldn’t I have been taken to Roundtable Hold by now? It’s the hub area with the blacksmith, it’s literally one of the most vital locations in the entire game.”

Even now, I’ve completely forgotten where I was when Melina finally showed up to invite me there.


EDIT: For reference, Leonine’s achievement is 59.8% on Steam. That’s actually lower than the achievements for the first two main bosses, both Godrick and Rennala, along with their prerequisite fights in Margit and the Red Wolf of Radagon.

I skipped straight to the 7th achievement on my first time experiencing Elden Ring.

to be honest as a PC player, who enjoyed pvping and testing builds, i spent most my time on modded saves at level 120 - 150  with the items i needed, and as much larval tears to change my build,  only this last week did i play through the entire base game and DLC legit (im only missing some extra bosses like malenia, placidusax / smaller dragons / midra from the dlc and bayle etc)  but man was it worth it, i remember struggling to literally kill margit,  but it can be done so easily as a level 1 samurai 😂 without even upgrading the sword, it made me realise just how bad i sucked when i first played

edit: in my defense elden ring is the only souls game ive grinded, i hardly played much of dark souls and only like 30 minutes of bloodborne,  i had no idea how poise worked, i didnt understand the effects of status' or the buffs that talismans give etc,  but now i know all them, and how to make use of them for each boss situation

snippet.textDisplay: This is actually remarkably common across games on Steam for various reasons. Achievement tracking is not available in every region, for one, so it’s not so much that 22.5% of players simply haven’t gotten the achievement, but some have and it isn’t tracked because that statistic is not shared with Steam. A portion of that percentage is also likely the demographic of players who purchased the game but don’t play it.
snippet.textOriginal: This is actually remarkably common across games on Steam for various reasons. Achievement tracking is not available in every region, for one, so it’s not so much that 22.5% of players simply haven’t gotten the achievement, but some have and it isn’t tracked because that statistic is not shared with Steam. snippet.textDisplay:
Because I like to FAFO in these types of games it took me about 15 hours of game play and at level 40 I finally got to the round table.  I explored places I definitely wasn’t supposed to be in yet before finding out about the Roundtable Hold.  And then when I got there I spent hours trying to beat that “invader” in the lower room.  With just the initial magic bolt spell as my highest DPS spell at the time.  It wasn’t until I was talking about the game and my progress with my DnD group that they all informed me about what I needed to do to go get better spells.

This is the first souls game I actually invested time into and had no idea what I was doing.  Still don’t.

snippet.textDisplay: Well I bought it when it won game of the year. Picked it up 3 times and gave up. I am someone who plays games at easiest mod. when buying, I knew Elden Ring is not a game created for causal and fun gamer like me, but still wanted to try it. Finally, I saw a video on YouTube "how gaming is for non gamers". In that video a gamer asked his non gamer gf to play elden ring till she beats any one boss of the game (outside of the tutorial). When I saw that even a non gamer was able to kill a boss after many tries, i decided to stick with the game till the end That was a month and a half ago. Now have only 3 platinum trophies on playstation. Spiderman Miles Morales, Spiderman 2 and Elden Ring. Finished Wukong just day before yesterday. And beaten Hades 10 times (to get true ending) in between the two games Getting back to very easy mode gameplay feels unattractive now.
